Look at the relationship between worldwide earnings and domestic earnings

ggplot(dat, aes(worldwide_earnings, domestic_earnings))+
  geom_point()+geom_smooth(method = "lm")+ggtitle("Relationship between Worldwide Earnings and Domestic Earnings")

Look at the relationship between worldwide earnings and rating by budget

dat2<-filter(dat,!is.na(budget),worldwide_earnings<1.5e+09)
ggplot(dat2, aes(worldwide_earnings,rating,color=budget))+
  geom_point()+geom_smooth(method="lm",se=FALSE)+ggtitle("Relationship between Worldwide Earnings and Rating")

Look at the relationship between mpaa rating and genre

dat3<-filter(dat,!is.na(mpaa))
ggplot(dat3, aes(mpaa,color=genre,fill=genre))+
  geom_bar()

Multi-step Visualization

Look at the density of genre of different rating

ggplot(dat, aes(genre,color=rating,fill=rating))+
  geom_density()

Flip x,y axis to make more sense out of the plotting

ggplot(dat, aes(rating,color=genre,fill=genre))+
  geom_density(alpha=0.2)

Density of Docmumentary looks odd, filter data

dat4<-filter(dat,genre!="Documentary")
ggplot(dat4, aes(rating,color=genre,fill=genre))+
  geom_density(alpha=0.2)

Further examine time series of rating

ggplot(dat, aes(year,rating))+
  geom_bar(stat = "identity")

Look at Genre rating density post 1980, excluding Documentary

dat5<-filter(dat4,year>1980)
ggplot(dat5, aes(rating,color=genre,fill=genre))+
  geom_density(alpha=0.2)+ggtitle("Genre Rating Density")

Summary

The findings that interest me the most are: 1. its obvious that worldwide earings and domestic earnings are positively related, while rating doesnt necessarily relate to earnings; 2. most of the action movies are actually rated as PG-13 as oppose to R (out of my expectation); 3.in general, animations are most highly-rated, followed by action movies, while short movies generally receive lower rating.
